---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import LayerSection from '../components/LayerSection.astro';
import { memLayers } from '../data/memLayers.js';
import CacheSim from '../components/CacheSim.svelte';
import AddressTranslation from '../components/AddressTranslation.svelte';
import MemoryHierarchy from '../components/MemoryHierarchy.astro';
import StackHeap from '../components/StackHeap.svelte';
import Allocator from '../components/Allocator.svelte';
import GarbageCollector from '../components/GarbageCollector.svelte';
import Why from '../components/Why.astro';
import Takeaway from '../components/Takeaway.astro';
import Advanced from '../components/Advanced.astro';
import Quiz from '../components/Quiz.svelte';
import PrevNext from '../components/PrevNext.astro';
import SeeAlso from '../components/SeeAlso.astro';
const L = Object.fromEntries(memLayers.map((l) => [l.id, l]));
const title = 'THE STACK — memory';
const description = 'A deep dive into memory: the stack and heap, allocation and garbage collection, caches and locality, the hierarchy, virtual memory and the TLB.';
---
<Base {title} {description} layers={memLayers}>
  <div slot="hero">
    <div class="kicker">A deep dive into layer 10</div>
    <h1 class="title">THE <em>MEMORY</em><br />STACK</h1>
    <p class="lede">"Memory" looks like one flat array of bytes — but a program has to carve it up (the stack and the heap), manage it (allocate, free, or collect), and then the hardware has to reach it fast (caches, the hierarchy, virtual memory). Two stories about the same bytes: how they're placed, and how they're found.</p>
    <div class="hero-meta"><a class="back-link" href="/">← back to the full stack</a> · addresses → stack & heap → allocation → GC → cache → hierarchy → virtual memory → TLB</div>
  </div>

  <LayerSection {...L.M0}>
    <p class="prose">At bottom, RAM is one enormous <b>array of bytes</b>, each with a numeric <span class="hl">address</span>. The CPU asks for an address and gets back the byte — that's the whole interface. Everything else is making that fast.</p>
    <Takeaway>Memory's interface is trivial — addressed bytes — so the entire stack above it exists to hide how slow reaching a far one really is.</Takeaway>
    <Advanced>
      <p>That uniform address space isn't all RAM. With <b>memory-mapped I/O</b>, ranges of addresses are wired to device registers instead of memory, so a plain load or store to the right address controls a disk, NIC, or GPU — which is why those regions must be marked <i>uncacheable</i> and why <code>volatile</code> exists in C.</p>
      <p>And the CPU isn't the only thing that touches memory. <b>DMA</b> (direct memory access) lets a device read and write RAM on its own while the CPU does other work, signalling completion with an interrupt — essential for throughput, but the reason caches and devices need careful coherence so the CPU doesn't read stale bytes a device just overwrote.</p>
    </Advanced>
    <Why
      problem="A program needs somewhere to keep values, and the CPU needs a uniform way to read and write them."
      idea="Expose memory as a flat, numbered array of bytes: give an address, get (or set) a byte."
      tradeoff="The model is simple but the physics isn't — main memory is far and slow relative to the CPU, so a naive read stalls it for hundreds of cycles."
      next="Before worrying about speed: how does a program decide which bytes to use?"
    />
  </LayerSection>

  <LayerSection {...L.M1}>
    <p class="prose">A program carves its address space into two regions. The <b>stack</b> grows and shrinks automatically with function calls — each call pushes a frame of locals, each return pops it. The <b>heap</b> is for data that must outlive a call; you allocate from it by hand, and it stays until freed.</p>
    <StackHeap client:visible />
    <Takeaway>The stack is automatic and call-scoped; the heap is manual and long-lived — where a value lives is decided by how long it needs to survive.</Takeaway>
    <Advanced>
      <p>The two regions grow <i>toward</i> each other from opposite ends of the address space — the stack downward, the heap upward — historically so a single contiguous space could flex between them. The stack is cheap precisely because allocation is just adjusting one register, the <b>stack pointer</b>; the cost is that the OS can't grow it freely, so blowing past its limit (deep or infinite recursion) triggers a <b>stack overflow</b>, usually caught by an unmapped <b>guard page</b>.</p>
      <p>This layout is also a security frontier: because return addresses live on the stack, overrunning a local buffer can overwrite them, which is why systems add stack <b>canaries</b>, non-executable stacks (<code>W^X</code>), and <b>ASLR</b> to randomize where everything lands.</p>
    </Advanced>
    <Why
      problem="A program has short-lived locals tied to a function call and long-lived data that must outlast it — and these want opposite treatment."
      idea="Use a stack that pushes and pops frames automatically with calls, and a heap you allocate from explicitly for anything that must persist."
      tradeoff="Stack memory is effortless but vanishes on return; heap memory persists but you own its lifetime — and getting that wrong is a whole class of bugs."
      next="So how is that heap actually carved up and handed out?"
    />
  </LayerSection>

  <LayerSection {...L.M2}>
    <p class="prose">The heap is managed by an <b>allocator</b>. <code>malloc(n)</code> finds a run of <i>n</i> contiguous free cells; <code>free</code> returns a block to the pool. But freeing in any order leaves <span class="hl">holes</span> — and a request can fail even when enough total space is free, just because it's scattered. That's <b>external fragmentation</b>.</p>
    <Allocator client:visible />
    <Takeaway>An allocator hands out contiguous runs and reclaims them on free; the catch is fragmentation — free space that exists but is too broken up to use.</Takeaway>
    <Advanced>
      <p>There are two fragmentations. <b>External</b> is the scattered-gaps problem shown here; <b>internal</b> is the waste <i>inside</i> a block when the allocator rounds your request up to a fixed <b>size class</b>. Real allocators lean into the latter on purpose: <b>slab</b> and <b>segregated-free-list</b> designs keep separate pools per size, so a request of that size is an O(1) pop and same-sized frees coalesce trivially.</p>
      <p>They also fight contention and locality: modern allocators (tcmalloc, jemalloc) give each thread its own <b>per-thread cache</b> to avoid a global lock, and the underlying memory comes from the OS in page-sized chunks via <code>mmap</code> or <code>sbrk</code> — so a <code>free</code> rarely returns memory to the OS, it just recycles it within the process.</p>
    </Advanced>
    <Why
      problem="The heap serves allocations of all sizes in any order, and must find room for each without moving the ones already in use."
      idea="Track free space and fit each request into a gap (first-fit, best-fit, …), returning freed blocks to the pool for reuse."
      tradeoff="Repeated alloc/free shatters memory into unusable gaps, so allocators must compact, coalesce neighbours, or hand out fixed-size slabs — none free."
      next="Manual freeing is error-prone, so many languages free memory for you."
    />
  </LayerSection>

  <LayerSection {...L.M3}>
    <p class="prose">Forgetting to <code>free</code> leaks memory; freeing too early corrupts it. So managed languages add a <b>garbage collector</b>: it treats your live variables as <span class="hl">roots</span>, follows every reference to find what's still reachable, and reclaims the rest. The classic algorithm is <b>mark and sweep</b>.</p>
    <GarbageCollector client:visible />
    <Takeaway>A garbage collector frees memory by reachability: anything you can still reach from a root is kept, everything else is collected — no manual free, at the cost of a tracing pause.</Takeaway>
    <Advanced>
      <p>Naive mark-and-sweep must pause the whole program and leaves the heap fragmented. Production collectors exploit the <b>generational hypothesis</b> — most objects die young — by collecting a small <b>nursery</b> often and the old generation rarely, which cuts the work dramatically. Many also <b>compact</b> survivors into one end of the heap, eliminating fragmentation and making allocation a pointer bump.</p>
      <p>To collect <i>concurrently</i> without freezing the program, the GC needs a <b>write barrier</b>: a hook on every pointer store that tells the collector when mutation might hide a still-reachable object, the classic tri-color invariant. This is the deep trade-off versus manual management and <code>malloc</code> — you give up control of <i>when</i> work happens in exchange for safety.</p>
    </Advanced>
    <Why
      problem="Manual memory management is a relentless source of bugs — leaks, double-frees, use-after-free — that are easy to introduce and hard to find."
      idea="Let a collector decide what’s garbage by tracing references from the roots; whatever it can’t reach can’t be used again, so it’s safe to reclaim."
      tradeoff="You trade those bugs for the collector’s cost: CPU spent tracing and pauses that can interrupt the program at awkward moments."
      next="That’s how memory is placed and managed. Now: how does the hardware reach it fast?"
    />
  </LayerSection>

  <LayerSection {...L.M4}>
    <p class="prose">A <b>cache</b> is a small, fast store near the CPU. A miss doesn't fetch one byte — it loads a whole <span class="hl">line</span> of neighbours, betting on <b>locality</b>: code usually touches nearby addresses next. Evict a line and touching it again misses anew.</p>
    <CacheSim client:visible />
    <Takeaway>Caches win on locality: one miss pulls in a line so the next several accesses hit — until that line gets evicted.</Takeaway>
    <Advanced>
      <p>A real cache isn't fully associative like the model here — checking every line per access is too expensive. Instead it's <b>set-associative</b>: an address's middle bits select one <i>set</i>, and a line may live in any of that set's few <b>ways</b> (8- or 16-way is typical). The catch is <b>conflict misses</b> — addresses that map to the same set evict each other even while the rest of the cache sits empty, which is why striding through memory at an unlucky power-of-two can crater performance.</p>
      <p>Writes need a policy too. <b>Write-back</b> caches mark a line <i>dirty</i> and flush it only on eviction (fast, but RAM is temporarily stale); <b>write-through</b> updates RAM every time (simple, more traffic). And on a write miss, <b>write-allocate</b> first pulls the line in to modify it, versus write-no-allocate which writes straight past the cache.</p>
    </Advanced>
    <Why
      problem="Main memory is hundreds of cycles away; reading it for every access would leave the CPU mostly idle."
      idea="Keep recently and nearby-used data in a small fast cache, fetching whole lines so spatial locality turns one slow miss into many fast hits."
      tradeoff="Caches are tiny, so they evict; bad locality (random access, huge working sets) defeats them and exposes the full memory latency."
      next="One cache isn't enough — there's a whole hierarchy of them."
    />
  </LayerSection>

  <LayerSection {...L.M5}>
    <p class="prose">No single memory is both huge and fast, so the machine stacks several: tiny fast registers, then L1/L2/L3 caches, then RAM, then disk — each step bigger, slower, and farther from the core.</p>
    <MemoryHierarchy />
    <Takeaway>The hierarchy is a speed-vs-size bargain: the closer to the CPU, the faster and smaller; the farther, the larger and slower.</Takeaway>
    <Advanced>
      <p>On a multi-core chip each core has private L1/L2 caches, so the same line can sit in several at once — and a write to one must not be invisible to the others. A <b>cache-coherence</b> protocol keeps them consistent; the classic is <b>MESI</b>, tagging every line <b>M</b>odified, <b>E</b>xclusive, <b>S</b>hared, or <b>I</b>nvalid. Before a core can write, it must gain exclusive ownership, invalidating every other copy.</p>
      <p>That handshake is why <b>false sharing</b> hurts so much: two cores updating <i>different</i> variables that happen to share one 64-byte line ping-pong ownership back and forth, each invalidating the other, even though there's no real data dependency — a top cause of mysteriously slow parallel code.</p>
    </Advanced>
    <Why
      problem="We want memory that is simultaneously enormous and single-cycle fast — physically impossible at any price."
      idea="Layer storage by speed: keep the hottest data in tiny fast levels and let it spill outward to larger, slower ones as it cools."
      tradeoff="It only works when access patterns are predictable; the hierarchy is invisible until a cache miss or page fault makes it suddenly, painfully visible."
      next="Above the physical hierarchy sits an illusion: every program thinks it owns all of memory."
    />
  </LayerSection>

  <LayerSection {...L.M6}>
    <p class="prose">Each program sees its own clean <b>virtual</b> address space. The MMU translates a virtual address — split into a <span class="hl">page</span> number and an offset — to a physical one, by looking the page up in a <b>page table</b>. If a page isn't resident (its entry is marked not-present), the lookup raises a <b>page fault</b>: the CPU traps to the OS, which brings the page in from disk into a free frame, updates the table, and restarts the instruction. That's what lets the address space be larger than physical RAM — and why a access that misses to disk is thousands of times slower.</p>
    <AddressTranslation client:visible />
    <Takeaway>Virtual memory gives every process a private address space; a page table maps its virtual pages to wherever they physically live.</Takeaway>
    <SeeAlso slug="os" note="the OS owns that page table, and uses it to isolate one process from another" />
    <Advanced>
      <p>A single flat page table for a 64-bit space would be astronomically large, so real systems use a <b>multi-level</b> (radix) table — x86-64 walks four levels, slicing the virtual address into 9-bit indexes that each select the next table down. Most of the tree is never allocated, so a sparse address space costs almost nothing; the price is that a miss now means up to four dependent memory reads to translate one address.</p>
      <p><b>Huge pages</b> (2 MB or 1 GB instead of 4 KB) attack this directly: a larger page covers more memory per entry, so the walk is shorter and far fewer translations are needed — a big win for databases and VMs, at the cost of coarser granularity and more wasted memory when a page is only partly used.</p>
    </Advanced>
    <Why
      problem="Many programs run at once and must not see or clobber each other's memory, yet each wants a simple contiguous space."
      idea="Give each process virtual addresses and translate them per-page to physical frames through a page table the OS controls — adding isolation and the freedom to relocate or page out memory."
      tradeoff="Every access now needs a translation (and a possible page fault to disk), which would be ruinous without a cache for the translations."
      next="That cache is the TLB."
    />
  </LayerSection>

  <LayerSection {...L.M7}>
    <p class="prose">Walking the page table on every access would be far too slow, so the MMU caches recent translations in the <span class="hl">TLB</span>. A hit skips the walk entirely; a miss pays for the walk once, then caches the result.</p>
    <Takeaway>The TLB is a cache for address translation — the same locality trick, applied to page lookups instead of data.</Takeaway>
    <Advanced>
      <p>The TLB is tiny — often only a few dozen to a few hundred entries — because it sits on the critical path of every access and is itself usually set-associative. Since one 4 KB entry covers just 4 KB, a working set spread over many pages can <b>thrash</b> the TLB even while the data caches hit fine; this is a major reason huge pages help, since one entry then covers 2 MB and stretches the same TLB over 512× the memory.</p>
      <p>A naive <b>context switch</b> must flush the TLB, because the same virtual address means different physical memory in another process; modern CPUs avoid that by tagging entries with an <b>address-space ID</b> (ASID/PCID) so multiple processes' translations can coexist. On a miss, hardware (x86) or the OS (some RISC designs) performs the multi-level page-table walk and refills the entry.</p>
    </Advanced>
    <Why
      problem="A page-table walk is itself several memory accesses; doing one per instruction would erase the benefit of virtual memory."
      idea="Cache the most recent virtual-page → physical-frame mappings in a tiny, fast TLB right in the MMU."
      tradeoff="The TLB is small, so programs that touch many pages thrash it (TLB misses), and a context switch can flush it entirely."
      next="Put it all together and follow one load from address to byte."
    />
  </LayerSection>

  <LayerSection {...L.M8}>
    <p class="prose">One load, end to end: the virtual address is translated (TLB, else a page-table walk), then the physical address is looked up in the caches (L1 → L2 → L3), and only on a full miss does it reach <b>RAM</b> — hundreds of cycles later.</p>
    <Takeaway>A single memory read is a gauntlet of caches and translations, all racing to avoid the long trip to RAM.</Takeaway>
    <Advanced>
      <p>When physical RAM fills, that final fallback gets a step uglier: the OS must <b>evict</b> a resident page to disk to make room. True <b>LRU</b> (least-recently-used) is too costly to track per access, so kernels approximate it with the <b>clock</b> algorithm — pages sit in a ring, each with a hardware-set <i>referenced</i> bit; a sweeping hand clears set bits and evicts the first page it finds already clear, giving recently-touched pages a second chance.</p>
      <p>Pick badly and the system <b>thrashes</b>: it spends more time paging to and from disk than computing, because the working set simply doesn't fit. The whole gauntlet above — caches, TLB, page tables — is really one idea applied at every scale: keep the hot data close, and pay dearly only when the prediction is wrong.</p>
    </Advanced>
    <Why
      problem="The flat ‘give address, get byte’ model hides translation, several cache levels, and a latency cliff — until performance depends on them."
      idea="Compose the pieces: translate the address, check each cache level in turn, and fall back to RAM (or disk) only when nothing closer has it."
      tradeoff="Each layer adds speed on a hit and a penalty on a miss, so real performance lives or dies by locality and working-set size."
      next="Zoom back out: this is what the main stack's Memory-hierarchy layer is doing under every program."
    />
  </LayerSection>

  <Quiz slug="memory" client:visible />
  <PrevNext slug="memory" />
</Base>

<style>
  .back-link{color:var(--accent,var(--signal))}
</style>
